{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20902"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20902"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.13,0.18,0.19,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97405"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80016"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12470"},{"type":"tags","id":"12724"},{"type":"tags","id":"12726"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33210"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97405"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory tests would be most appropriate for confirming the diagnosis of coccidioidomycosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enzyme immunoassay","Agglutination test","Western blot test","Complement fixation test","Precipitation test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplement fixation test\u003C/strong\u003E confirms coccidioidomycosis, a fungal disease caused by \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides immitis\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides posadasii\u003C/em\u003E. This diagnostic method detects antibodies that bind to antigens and fix (consume) complement in the patient\u0027s serum or cerebrospinal fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen performing this test, the laboratory combines the patient\u0027s sample with standardized amounts of complement and specific \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides\u003C/em\u003E antigens. The extent of complement consumption correlates with the antibody concentration present. This technique can quantify both IgM and IgG antibodies, yielding titer values that are valuable for tracking infection progression and evaluating treatment efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less suitable for diagnosing coccidioidomycosis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgglutination test\u003C/strong\u003E - While useful for some infections, it is not the preferred method for coccidioidomycosis diagnosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzyme immunoassay\u003C/strong\u003E - Although sometimes used, it is not as specific as complement fixation for coccidioidomycosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWestern blot test\u003C/strong\u003E - More commonly used for confirming HIV or Lyme disease, not typically used for fungal infections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrecipitation test\u003C/strong\u003E - Less sensitive than complement fixation for detecting coccidioidomycosis antibodies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplement fixation tests, despite being labor-intensive and requiring numerous controls, remain valuable diagnostic tools for coccidioidomycosis due to their accuracy and ability to provide quantitative results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complement fixation tests measure complement-consuming antibodies in serum or cerebrospinal fluid for diagnosing certain viral and fungal infections.","Coccidioidomycosis is a fungal infection caused by Coccidioides species that can be diagnosed using complement fixation tests.","Complement fixation tests can detect both IgM and IgG antibodies and provide quantitative results through antibody titers."],"references":["Vazquez-Pertejo MT, Bush LM. Immunologic Tests for Infectious Disease. Merck Manual Professional Edition. January 2025. Available from: https://www.merckmanuals.com/professional/infectious-diseases/laboratory-diagnosis-of-infectious-..."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20902"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80016"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T17:20:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T17:21:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13777"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97405"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12470","links":{"self":"https://app